        <abstract>
            <p>Huxley feels he can accept the Edinburgh lecture invitation.</p> 
<p>Also tells JDH he is preparing a paper for Linnean Society on classification which will uphold evolution ["On the classification of the animal kingdom", <hi rend="italic">J. Linn. Soc. Lond. (Zool.)</hi> 12 (1876): 199–226]. He has thrown overboard all his old ideas of definite demarcation. He will make a clean breast of it, and will bear hard on necessity of all such ideas as Haeckel’s in dealing with systematic zoology.</p> 
        </abstract>
